DOCUMENT();    

loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "PGML.pl",       # Ensure PGML is loaded
  "PGcourse.pl",
  'parserPopUp.pl'
);

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$popup1 = PopUp([ '?', 'dx', 'dy' ], 'dy');
$popup2 = PopUp([ '?', 'dx', 'dy' ], 'dx');
## $dropdown1 = DropDown([ 'Red', 'Blue', 'Green' ], 'Green');
# $dropdown2 = DropDown([ 'Red', 'Blue', 'Green' ], 'Red', placeholder => 'Select One');

Context("Numeric");
Context()->variables->add(y => "Real");

$a = random(2,9,1);

$integrandWashers = Formula("pi*($a * y**2)**2");
$integrandShells = Formula("2*pi*x*(1 - sqrt(x / $a))");
$volume = Formula("pi*$a**2/5");

BEGIN_PGML
The volume of the solid obtained by rotating the region bounded by  
[``` x = [$a] y^2, y = 1, x = 0, ```]
about the [`y`]-axis can be computed using the method of disks via an integral:

>>[``V = \int_a^b``] [________]{$integrandWashers} [________]{$popup1}<<

with limits of integration [` a = `] [_____]{0} and [` b = `] [_____]{1}. 

The volume of this solid can also be computed using cylindrical shells via an integral:


>>[``V = \int_\alpha^\beta``] [________]{$integrandShells} [________]{$popup2}<<

with limits of integration [` \alpha = `] [_____]{0} and [` \beta = `] [_____]{$a}.

In either case, the volume is [` V = `] [________]{$volume} cubic units.
END_PGML


